<td align="center">
<div class="poemtitle">Benvolio’s Aside</div> 
<br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('dion')">by Brian Dion</a> <br>
<br>
<br>
<table cellpadding="20" cellspacing="0"><tr><td>
Time consumed my pity long ago<br>
and blame’s a knife that pierces all the players.<br>
So when the curtain comes down on the show<br>
the guilty stack in layers upon layers.<br>
The meddling friar, Tybalt to be sure;<br>
for R. &amp; J. all I will say is this:<br>
When love casts out its charming, perfumed lure,<br>
the fish it hooks deserves its prickly kiss.<br>
<br>
There’s only one I mourn.  Mercutio,<br>
who spreads his wit and blood across our stage.<br>
I swoon to his sad oratorio<br>
when the sword invades his bony cage;<br>
and then he dies.  I find myself struck dumb.<br>
To all the rest I curse and bite my thumb.<br>
</td>
<td align="right"><img src="images/benvolio.jpg"><br><span class="byartist">Donald Zirilli</span></td>
</tr></table>
</td>
</tr>
